31:07.566 --> 31:12.604 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're registered, counted,
their nationalities
are determined, and the point is
to kind of

31:12.704 --> 31:14.372 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
know who's coming into Europe.

31:14.473 --> 31:16.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: But how is that
protecting
Europe's borders?

31:17.042 --> 31:23.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS BOROWSKI: The bottom line
is that it's
up to the Greeks to protect the
borders here.

31:23.281 --> 31:25.450 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're here to support them in
any way we possibly
can.

31:25.550 --> 31:29.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: For more than a
week, the
Portuguese have not seen any
migrants. The

31:30.088 --> 31:36.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
police don bulletproof life
jackets, in case
they encounter violent
smugglers, or worse.

31:36.895 --> 31:42.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's a boat in distress. The
skipper cranks
up the engines to 45 knots.

31:42.901 --> 31:51.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The calm weather is perfect for
crossing from
Turkey. Other European civilian
volunteers

31:51.977 --> 32:03.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have already arrived to ensure
there's no
loss of life. This is a familiar
scenario.

32:03.455 --> 32:08.126 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The cheap outboards either die
mid-channel,
or the migrants cut the engines
and call for

32:08.226 --> 32:15.901 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
help by mobile phone.

32:16.001 --> 32:37.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a problem with the
engine, they shout.
The dinghy is carrying 58
people, including

32:37.155 --> 32:44.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
18 mainly small children. The
Portuguese prime
concern is that, in their haste
to get off,

32:45.030 --> 32:49.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the refugees will destabilize
the vessel and
it will capsize.

32:49.734 --> 32:57.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: Hold the line. You hold the
line here.

32:57.742 --> 33:02.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Scores of
people have drowned
in these waters so far this
year. As many

33:02.914 --> 33:05.650 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as 4,000 died in 2015.

33:05.750 --> 33:09.120 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Where are both of you from?

33:09.221 --> 33:10.889 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
MAN: From Syria.

33:10.989 --> 33:12.624 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Yes.

33:12.724 --> 33:19.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What do you think of this? What
do you think
of the way that you're being
met?

33:19.798 --> 33:23.368 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: It's good, good. Thank you.

33:23.468 --> 33:27.606 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: The gentle sea
state helps
the Portuguese agents.

33:27.706 --> 33:35.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: Today, it's them. Tomorrow,
maybe Portuguese
can need people, too. So, we
have to take

33:35.247 --> 33:36.915 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
care of each other.

33:37.015 --> 33:43.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: A normal day. The boat have
a problem
with the engine. It cannot move.
The people

33:44.022 --> 33:49.861 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
inside, we have too many
children, two sick
guys, in this case, we have to
put on board

33:49.961 --> 33:52.931 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and take them ashore to have a
medical test.

33:53.031 --> 34:07.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN: You wait. You wait for us
to call you,
OK? Wait. Wait. Wait. Wait.
Wait.

34:07.679 --> 34:13.451 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Like many of
those on board,
Abdullah Harmoush is from
Latakia on Syria's

34:13.551 --> 34:15.787 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
coast, the home town of
President Bashar al-Assad.

34:15.887 --> 34:21.526 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABDULLAH HARMOUSH, Refugee:
There are many
troubles in my city because of
the violence,

34:21.626 --> 34:25.130 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and it's that we couldn't stay
there in Syria.

34:25.230 --> 34:39.811 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, we left Syria to take
refugee. It was
a very good response from the
police. We was

34:39.911 --> 34:48.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very afraid in the sea, but when
we entered
the water of Greece, we have the
support very

34:48.420 --> 34:55.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
quickly. We are expecting very,
very fast
response from the police in the
sea from Greece.

34:55.293 --> 35:03.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's really an amazing feel that
we -- at
the time we entered the water of
Greece, we

35:03.168 --> 35:08.873 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are rescued, and we are very,
very, very happy
about it, here in this boat.

35:08.974 --> 35:14.112 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Acting as
purely a rescue
service, which is what you're
doing, aren't

35:14.212 --> 35:17.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you actually encouraging more
people to come
because they know they're going
to be safe?

35:18.016 --> 35:24.022 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CHRIS BOROWSKI: We do not
encourage people
to come here. We're here to help
patrol the

35:24.122 --> 35:30.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
waters. And once the migrants
cross in, we
are -- if it's a
search-and-rescue operation,

35:30.862 --> 35:36.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we have to help them get to the
-- get on
the boats, and then we have to
allow them

35:36.868 --> 35:40.505 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to come to Greece to then
register them and
allow them to seek asylum.

35:40.605 --> 35:43.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: But some of the
people on
this boat were saying, we knew
we were going

35:44.075 --> 35:48.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be rescued, so we just set
off. So isn't
that just encouraging people?

35:48.146 --> 35:52.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS BOROWSKI: What we are
doing is, we are
supporting the Greeks in
patrolling their

35:52.317 --> 35:59.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
borders and we are doing all we
can to both
make sure that we both register
everybody

36:00.025 --> 36:05.130 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who comes here and rescuing
those who needs
-- who needs rescues.

36:05.230 --> 36:10.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: In the past 10
days, NATO
has deployed to reinforce
Europe's borders.

36:10.568 --> 36:15.140 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are five ships out in the
international
waters of the Aegean Sea, which
divided Greece

36:15.240 --> 36:17.042 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
from Turkey.

36:17.142 --> 36:20.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, NATO insists that it's not
going to be
intercepting refugee boats and
turning them

36:20.912 --> 36:26.184 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
back. They will adhere to
international treaties,
which require them to go to the
help of people

36:26.284 --> 36:32.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in distress upon the sea. That
means that
people picked up by NATO vessels
will be returned

36:32.791 --> 36:34.859 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to Turkey.

36:34.959 --> 36:40.965 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Will this strategy work?
Professor Christodoulos
Yiallouridis, dean of Athens'
Panteion University,

36:41.066 --> 36:42.867 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
believes it could make a
difference.

36:42.967 --> 36:46.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTODOULOS YIALLOURIDIS,
Panteion University
(through translator): NATO can't
stop them

36:46.271 --> 36:51.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coming. She can, however, assist
in restricting
the flow of migrants simply
because of her

36:51.709 --> 36:57.715 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
presence. It will be known that
NATO is waiting
for them, and this should act as
a deterrent.

36:57.816 --> 37:05.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: NATO didn't
deter these 90
Afghans picked up by the Greek
coast guard.

37:05.156 --> 37:07.892 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How do you feel about being in
Europe?

37:07.992 --> 37:10.295 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MAN: We are feeling good. Good.

37:10.395 --> 37:14.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Among them,
Edriss Bayat,
who used to work as an
administrator for NATO

37:14.866 --> 37:16.701 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Afghanistan.

37:16.801 --> 37:19.003 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EDRISS BAYAT, Refugee: What do
you think about
the way Europe is reacting to
the refugee

37:19.104 --> 37:20.972 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
crisis?

37:21.072 --> 37:26.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, I think they are doing a
good job. At
least, they are -- they know
that who is entitled

37:26.945 --> 37:33.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to seek the assistance. And, for
example,
we come from Afghanistan, Iraq,
Syria, and

37:33.418 --> 37:37.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they are the people who very --
really need
to leave their country and --
because save

37:38.022 --> 37:39.757 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
their life.

37:39.858 --> 37:42.260 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MALCOLM BRABANT: But why
couldn't you stay
in another country like Turkey,
for example?

37:42.360 --> 37:44.496 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Why did you have to come to
Europe?

37:44.596 --> 37:49.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EDRISS BAYAT: Well, there is a
lot of issues
in Turkey, for example,
job-wise. They are

37:49.667 --> 37:58.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not giving you the immigrants.
You cannot
get like a permanent visa or a
Turkish passport

37:58.710 --> 38:00.278 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
or anything.

38:00.378 --> 38:06.885 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Where do you
want to go in
Europe? What do you want to do?

38:06.985 --> 38:10.155 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ABDULLAH HARMOUSH: For me, I
want to continue
my study and have a good future.

38:10.255 --> 38:14.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Do you want to
stay in Europe,
or do you want to go back to
Syria? What do

38:14.225 --> 38:15.927 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
you want to do?

38:16.027 --> 38:19.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ABDULLAH HARMOUSH: Of course,
when the war
is over, I will come back to my
country.

38:19.130 --> 38:22.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: And what do you
want to do
for your country when you...

38:22.300 --> 38:24.068 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ABDULLAH HARMOUSH: OK. Rebuild
it.

38:24.169 --> 38:28.006 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EDRISS BAYAT: I really wish to
have a safe
country. If our country gets
safe, we will

38:28.106 --> 38:29.941 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
go back.

38:30.041 --> 38:34.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: European Union
nations are
doing all they can to stem the
migrant tide,

38:34.712 --> 38:39.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but, as Middle Eastern violence
threatens
to draw in Turkey, the flow
shows no sign

38:40.051 --> 38:41.252 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of abating.

38:41.352 --> 38:46.491 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Malcolm Brabant
in Lesbos.

38:46.591 --> 38:59.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Iranians will go
to the polls
next week to elect a new
parliament and to

38:59.604 --> 39:03.274 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
choose the small group that will
pick the
next supreme leader.

39:03.374 --> 39:08.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of our colleagues from NPR
is just back
from a reporting trip to Iran,
and William

39:08.680 --> 39:10.448 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Brangham has that conversation.

39:10.548 --> 39:14.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The signing of
the landmark
nuclear deal with Iran was
supposed to begin

39:14.519 --> 39:19.123 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a new era of relations between
Iran and the
West. The deal would free Iran
from decades

39:19.224 --> 39:23.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of crippling economic sanctions,
while giving
the West some confidence that
Iran won't be

39:23.595 --> 39:25.730 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
able to develop a nuclear
weapon.

39:25.830 --> 39:29.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Many in the United States,
however, remain
wary of Iran's intentions,
including virtually

39:29.901 --> 39:34.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all the Republican candidates
running for
president. They all vow to
renegotiate the

39:34.272 --> 39:35.073 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
agreement.

39:35.173 --> 39:37.242 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But what is happening inside
Iran?

39:37.342 --> 39:40.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
National Public Radio's Steve
Inskeep is just
back from a reporting trip, and
he joins me

39:40.745 --> 39:41.679 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
now.

39:41.779 --> 39:43.047 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Steve, welcome back. And welcome
to the show.

39:43.147 --> 39:44.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP, National Public
Radio: Thanks.
Glad to be here.

39:45.016 --> 39:48.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The nuclear
deal has been
signed. Iran is freed somewhat
from these

39:48.319 --> 39:49.587 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
sanctions.

39:49.687 --> 39:52.390 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What is it like there? Are
things getting
better for Iranians?

39:52.490 --> 39:55.426 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
STEVE INSKEEP: No, not in
day-to-day life,
not yet.

39:55.526 --> 39:59.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, in talking with people
on the street,
which I find to be one of the
most productive

39:59.464 --> 40:03.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
things to do when traveling to
Iran, I find
a lot of pessimism. People have
gone through

40:03.968 --> 40:08.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
years of economic suffering.
Many people have
disagreed with the political
direction of

40:08.439 --> 40:10.208 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
their government.

40:10.308 --> 40:14.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And even though things are
moving, in their
point of view, in a more
optimistic direction,

40:14.145 --> 40:20.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's very slow. And of course
it's too early
to see any concrete economic
results from

40:20.518 --> 40:22.820 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the end of sanctions that just
happened a
few weeks ago.

40:22.920 --> 40:27.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There was a time when people
were saying just
the anticipation of the end of
sanctions was

40:27.659 --> 40:31.963 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
improving Iran's economy, but
that seems not
to have trickled down to
ordinary people.

40:32.063 --> 40:37.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But I don't
understand.
Rouhani was elected in no small
part to eliminate

40:37.568 --> 40:41.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sanctions, to improve relations
with the West,
to try to make the economy
better. Is this

40:42.006 --> 40:44.609 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the sense that it's not
happening fast enough
or not enough?

40:44.709 --> 40:46.611 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: That is exactly
right.

40:46.711 --> 40:51.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is this residue of support
for Hassan
Rouhani. I even found people in
centers of

40:51.582 --> 40:55.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
support for the prior president,
who was very
different, who said, yes, I
support Rouhani.

40:55.119 --> 40:56.988 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm with Rouhani.

40:57.088 --> 41:02.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think more liberal people
or Western-facing
people who want much greater
openness, who

41:02.994 --> 41:05.663 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
want much greater change have
been disappointed
not to see more.

41:05.763 --> 41:09.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And I know, in
one of your
reports this week, you reported
on how there

41:09.801 --> 41:13.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are certainly still some people
in Iran who
don't want any of those changes
to occur.

41:14.072 --> 41:15.973 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is it that they're afraid
of?

41:16.074 --> 41:20.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is it that they're worried
-- if business
starts to flourish, if the
economy gets better?

41:21.045 --> 41:22.880 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Help me understand what the
concern is.

41:22.980 --> 41:24.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: Well, on a basic
level, they're
afraid of us. They're afraid of
the United

41:25.016 --> 41:26.784 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
States.

41:26.884 --> 41:29.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This was a government that was
founded on
a few basic principles, and one
of them was

41:29.587 --> 41:34.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
opposition to the United States.
And the United
States was blamed for many of
Iran's previous

41:34.459 --> 41:40.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
problems before 1979. There's
been a longstanding
rivalry. They're aware of
profound distrust

41:40.498 --> 41:42.967 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in the United States of Iran.

41:43.067 --> 41:47.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so you have two governments
that are very
much at odds on everything other
than the

41:47.372 --> 41:52.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nuclear deal. And so, on one
level, it's as
simple as that. On another
level, you have

41:52.377 --> 41:59.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a government, a clerical-led
government, that
has elections, that has a
semblance of democracy,

41:59.550 --> 42:03.855 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
but that knows it is not
fundamentally supported
by a lot of people.

42:03.955 --> 42:07.492 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Some people might say the
majority of Iranians
oppose the government. I can't
go that far.

42:07.592 --> 42:11.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't know what the numbers
are. But it's
clear there is a lot of
cynicism, a lot of

42:11.629 --> 42:15.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
disappointment with this
government, and a
lot of impatience with this
government.

42:15.933 --> 42:20.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you're in charge, you
know that. And
so you wonder what's going to
happen next.

42:20.671 --> 42:23.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You don't want things to go the
wrong way
and for your government to fall.

42:23.574 --> 42:26.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: One of the
things that,
in the West, we like to tell
ourselves is

42:26.644 --> 42:31.249 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that it was the economic
sanctions that crippled
their economy and brought Iran
to the negotiating

42:31.349 --> 42:33.184 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
table.

42:33.284 --> 42:36.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of your reports really
detailed this
-- the cynicism almost that
people think that

42:36.587 --> 42:41.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some of the problems within Iran
might have
been because of corruption and
mismanagement

42:41.292 --> 42:42.460 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
within their own government.

42:42.560 --> 42:44.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: Oh, yes. No, this
was really
interesting.

42:44.462 --> 42:48.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was a talking point for
Iranians during
sanctions: Your sanctions aren't
really hurting

42:48.699 --> 42:51.335 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
us too much. It's other things
that are going
on here.

42:51.436 --> 42:56.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it's also something that a
lot of Iranians
firmly, genuinely believe, that
there were

42:56.541 --> 43:00.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ways that they found to get
around economic
sanctions. And, by the way,
during all my

43:00.411 --> 43:04.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
