45:16.647 --> 45:25.990 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STEVE INSKEEP: Glad to come.

45:26.090 --> 45:34.398 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight:
the loss of
a literary legend reclusive in
life, but renowned

45:34.498 --> 45:37.101 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for crafting one of the great
American novels.

45:37.201 --> 45:38.970 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And to Jeffrey Brown.

45:39.070 --> 45:42.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Harper Lee was a
little known
writer living in New York when
"To Kill a

45:42.673 --> 45:48.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mockingbird" was published in
1960. The book
would win the Pulitzer Prize a
year later,

45:48.613 --> 45:55.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sell more than 30 million copies
in 40 languages,
and be read and loved by
generations.

45:55.353 --> 46:03.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Its fame grew with the 1962 film
version starring
Gregory Peck as Atticus Finch,
father of the

46:03.260 --> 46:09.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
young narrator, Scout, and a
lawyer in a segregated
Alabama town who defends a black
man against

46:09.600 --> 46:11.202 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a rape charge.

46:11.302 --> 46:16.207 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a 1964 radio interview, Lee
said this about
"Mockingbird"'s enormous
success:

46:16.307 --> 46:18.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARPER LEE, Author, "To Kill a
Mockingbird":
My reaction to it wasn't one of
surprise.

46:18.109 --> 46:24.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was one of sheer numbness. It
was like
being hit over the head and
knocked cold.

46:24.281 --> 46:25.783 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:25.883 --> 46:30.655 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARPER LEE: I never expected
that the book
would sell in the first place.

46:30.755 --> 46:35.726 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: But in the
decades that followed,
Lee did little or no talking. It
was news

46:35.826 --> 46:41.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when she went to the White House
in 2007 to
accept a Presidential Medal of
Freedom.

46:41.565 --> 46:47.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead, she lived quietly most
of her life
in the town of Monroeville,
Alabama. And while

46:47.905 --> 46:54.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
readers waited, no other books
came, until
the surprise this past summer of
"Go Set a

46:54.311 --> 46:59.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Watchman," a book described as
written before
"Mockingbird," but only
discovered and published

46:59.583 --> 47:02.019 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
55 years later.

47:02.119 --> 47:07.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It drew more readers, mixed
reviews, and many
questions about the
circumstances of its writing

47:07.558 --> 47:09.694 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and publication.

47:09.794 --> 47:15.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Harper Lee died in her sleep
last night. She
was 89 years old.

47:15.366 --> 47:20.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And joining us now is novelist
and short story
writer Allan Gurganus. His books
include "Oldest

47:20.371 --> 47:24.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Living Confederate Widow Tells
All," "Plays
Well With Others," and most
recently "Local

47:24.709 --> 47:25.276 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Souls."

47:25.376 --> 47:26.911 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Allan, welcome to you.

47:27.011 --> 47:31.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What explains the popularity in
the end of
"To Kill a Mockingbird"?

47:31.415 --> 47:37.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLAN GURGANUS, Author, "Local
Souls": I think
it's a fable about the
extraordinarily difficult

47:37.922 --> 47:43.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
subject of race that presents
itself with
charm and a kind of innocence
that makes the

47:43.794 --> 47:47.364 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
investigation acceptable and
beguiling.

47:47.465 --> 47:53.938 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the name Scout of the
child is appropriate.
She's our representative in this
strange moral

47:54.038 --> 47:59.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
morass that she finds herself
in. And I think
she's spoken to a lot of people
over the years.

47:59.677 --> 48:05.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And set in its
particular time,
when you think of both the
historical qualities

48:05.449 --> 48:09.787 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and for you, as a writer, its
writing qualities.

48:09.887 --> 48:17.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLAN GURGANUS: It's a book with
a lot of
precision, a lot of poetic
passages about

48:17.261 --> 48:22.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
small-town life that rings
completely true,
as somebody who grew up in a
small town.

48:22.533 --> 48:28.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think, ethically, the
questions are
strenuous and difficult and
interesting. And

48:28.172 --> 48:35.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that combination of giving us
candy and salt
at the same time has made the
book so popular.

48:35.312 --> 48:38.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's also short, which is great
for junior
high school readers.

48:38.682 --> 48:40.284 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

48:40.384 --> 48:45.389 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALLAN GURGANUS: But it manages
to pull heartstrings
and ask big, big questions.

48:45.489 --> 48:50.261 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Not to be
underemphasized,
the length of a book sometimes,
right?

48:50.361 --> 48:51.729 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What about Harper Lee the
author?

48:51.829 --> 48:53.831 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ALLAN GURGANUS: No, and
especially for young
people.

48:53.931 --> 48:59.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What about Harper
Lee the author
and the sort of -- the mythology
of the -- that

48:59.270 --> 49:04.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
came to surround her as writing
this one book,
all but disappearing, people
waiting endlessly

49:05.042 --> 49:06.944 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for another book?

49:07.044 --> 49:14.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLAN GURGANUS: I think she was
a very shy,
charming person used to living
in a very small

49:14.285 --> 49:19.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
town, where everybody knew her,
and the attention
that she got when this novel
came out and

49:19.657 --> 49:24.929 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
became a bestseller for 88 weeks
was overwhelming.

49:25.029 --> 49:30.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She was also protecting her
private life,
her sexual life, which is a
decision that

49:30.668 --> 49:37.575 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I respect. And she just made a
decision not
to go public. I think the
pressure of following

49:37.675 --> 49:43.047 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a book that wins the Pulitzer
Prize can't
be overestimated.

49:43.147 --> 49:49.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And she was -- I think had set
out to write
a book that mythologized her
father, her actual

49:50.054 --> 49:55.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
lawyer father, in a way that met
her own standards.
He still spoke to her after she
had written

49:55.960 --> 50:01.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the book. And she was pleased
with what she
had done. And I think her
mission was in some

50:01.198 --> 50:03.067 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ways complete.

50:03.167 --> 50:06.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And then, of
course, there's
the "Go Set a Watchman," a very
strange episode,

50:07.037 --> 50:11.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
many questions that came about,
whether it
was an early draft of
"Mockingbird," whether

50:11.976 --> 50:14.478 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
she had agreed or should have
agreed to its
publication.

50:14.578 --> 50:18.983 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What, in the end, do you think
that we should
take from that?

50:19.083 --> 50:25.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALLAN GURGANUS: I think every
writer has two
or three novels hidden away in
drawers and

50:25.589 --> 50:29.360 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
closets that would ruin their
literary reputation.

50:29.460 --> 50:36.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for somebody to come in late
in your game
and public those with only half
of your permission

50:37.001 --> 50:44.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
may be a smart move in terms of
moneymaking,
but it was a devastating blow to
her reputation.

50:44.174 --> 50:48.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A lot of boys had been named
Atticus, and
people actually went to court to
have their

50:48.178 --> 50:54.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
